A paperfolding sequence is a sequence over the alphabet $\{-1, 1\}$ arising from iterated folding of paper. For a finite sequence of unfolding instructions $f \in \{-1,1\}^*$, the paperfolding sequence $P_f$ is defined recursively by:
\begin{align}
P_\epsilon &= \epsilon \\
P_{fa} &= (P_f) \, a \, (-P_f^R)
\end{align}
for $a \in \{-1,1\}$, where $\epsilon$ is the empty sequence, $-x$ negates each element of $x$, and $x^R$ reverses $x$. For an infinite sequence of unfolding instructions $f = f_0 f_1 f_2 \cdots \in \{-1,1\}^\omega$, the infinite paperfolding sequence $P_f$ is the unique limit of the finite sequences $P_{f_0 \cdots f_n}$. The run-length sequence $R_f$ records the lengths of maximal blocks of consecutive identical values in $P_f$. It is proven in the paper that: (1) $R_f$ has length $2^{n-1}$ when $|f|=n$, (2) the only run lengths are 1, 2, or 3, and (3) there is a finite automaton computing $R_f[n]$ for all paperfolding sequences simultaneously. Determine the complete list of palindromes that may appear in the run-length sequence of a paperfolding sequence.

Let $\mathbf{F}$ be a class of finite po-frames that is closed under generated subframes and p-morphic images (i.e., $\mathrm{sm}(\mathbf{F}) = \mathbf{F}$), and let $\mathsf{L} = \mathsf{L}(\mathbf{F})$ be a locally tabular intermediate logic. For any $n \geq 0$, let $\mathbf{M}^n = \mathbf{M}^n(\mathbf{F})$ denote the class of $n$-models over frames in $\mathbf{F}$, and let $\mathbf{M}^n_{ir}$ denote the class of p-irreducible $n$-models over frames in $\mathbf{F}$. For any substitution $\sigma:\{x_1,\dots,x_n\}\to \mathsf{Fm}^k$, define $H_\sigma: \mathbf{M}^k \to \mathbf{M}^n$ by $H_\sigma(\mathfrak{M}^k) = \sigma(\mathfrak{M}^k)$, where for a $k$-model $\mathfrak{M}^k = (W,R,w_0,V^k)$, the $n$-model $\sigma(\mathfrak{M}^k) = (W,R,w_0,V^n)$ is defined by $x_i \in V^n(w) \Leftrightarrow \mathfrak{M}^k \Vdash_w \sigma(x_i)$ for any $w \in W$ and $i = 1,\dots,n$. Two substitutions $\varepsilon, \sigma:\{x_1,\dots,x_n\}\to \mathsf{Fm}^k$ are equivalent in $\mathsf{L}$, written $\varepsilon =_{\mathsf{L}} \sigma$, if $\varepsilon(A) =_{\mathsf{L}} \sigma(A)$ for each formula $A$, i.e., $\vdash_{\mathsf{L}} \varepsilon(A) \leftrightarrow \sigma(A)$.

Now let $H:\mathbf{M}^k_{ir}\to \mathbf{M}^n$ be a function satisfying:
(i) for every $\mathfrak{M}^k \in \mathbf{M}^k_{ir}$, the $n$-model $H(\mathfrak{M}^k)$ has the same frame as the $k$-model $\mathfrak{M}^k$;
(ii) for every $\mathfrak{M}^k=(W,R,w_0,V^k) \in \mathbf{M}^k_{ir}$ and every $w\in W$, it holds that $H((\mathfrak{M}^k)_w)\thicksim (H(\mathfrak{M}^k))_w$ (where $(\mathfrak{M}^k)_w$ denotes the submodel generated by $w$, and $\thicksim$ denotes equivalence of models, i.e., they satisfy the same formulas);
(iii) if $\mathfrak{N}^k\equiv\mathfrak{M}^k$ (i.e., $\mathfrak{N}^k$ and $\mathfrak{M}^k$ are isomorphic), then $H(\mathfrak{N}^k)\thicksim H(\mathfrak{M}^k)$, for any $\mathfrak{M}^k,\mathfrak{N}^k\in \mathbf{M}^k_{ir}$.

What is the number of substitutions $\sigma:\{x_1,\dots,x_n\}\to \mathsf{Fm}^k$ (up to $=_{\mathsf{L}}$) such that $H(\mathfrak{M}^k)\thicksim H_\sigma(\mathfrak{M}^k)$ for each $\mathfrak{M}^k\in \mathbf{M}^k_{ir}$?

Let $\mathcal{G}$ be a generalized $n$-matrix ring. Recall that $\mathcal{G} = \bigoplus_{i,j \in \{1,\ldots,n\}} \mathcal{G}_{ij}$, where $\mathcal{G}_{ij} = \{(m_{kt}) : m_{kt} = m_{ij} \text{ if } (k,t)=(i,j), \text{ and } 0 \text{ otherwise}\}$ for $m_{ij} \in \mathcal{M}_{ij}$ (with $\mathcal{M}_{ii} = \mathcal{R}_i$ being rings and $\mathcal{M}_{ij}$ being $(\mathcal{R}_i, \mathcal{R}_j)$-bimodules for $i \neq j$). The center of $\mathcal{G}$ is
$$\mathcal{Z}(\mathcal{G}) = \left\{ \bigoplus_{i=1}^{n} r_{ii} \mid r_{ii} m_{ij} = m_{ij} r_{jj} \text{ for all } m_{ij} \in \mathcal{M}_{ij}, i \neq j \right\}.$$

Consider a biadditive map $B : \mathcal{G} \times \mathcal{G} \to \mathcal{G}$ satisfying:
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] $B(\mathcal{G}_{pp}, \mathcal{G}_{qq}) \subseteq \mathcal{G}_{pp} \cap \mathcal{G}_{qq}$; $B(\mathcal{G}_{pp}, \mathcal{G}_{rs}) \in \mathcal{G}_{rs}$ and $B(\mathcal{G}_{rs}, \mathcal{G}_{pp}) \in \mathcal{G}_{rs}$; $B(\mathcal{G}_{pq}, \mathcal{G}_{rs}) = 0$ (for $p \neq q$, $r \neq s$);
\item[(ii)] if $B\left(\bigoplus_{1 \leq p \neq q \leq n} c_{pq}, \mathcal{G}_{nn}\right) = 0$ or $B\left(\bigoplus_{1 \leq r < n} \mathcal{G}_{rr}, \bigoplus_{1 \leq p \neq q \leq n} c_{pq}\right) = 0$, then $\bigoplus_{1 \leq p \neq q \leq n} c_{pq} = 0$;
\item[(iii)] $B(\mathcal{G}_{nn}, a_{nn}) = 0$ implies $a_{nn} = 0$;
\item[(iv)] if $B\left(\bigoplus_{p=1}^{n} c_{pp}, \mathcal{G}_{rs}\right) = B\left(\mathcal{G}_{rs}, \bigoplus_{p=1}^{n} c_{pp}\right) = 0$ for all $1 \leq r \neq s \leq n$, then $\bigoplus_{p=1}^{n-1} c_{pp} \oplus (-c_{nn}) \in \mathcal{Z}(\mathcal{G})$;
\item[(v)] $B(c_{pp}, d_{pp}) = B(d_{pp}, c_{pp})$ and $B(c_{pp}, d_{pp}) d_{pn} d_{nn} = d_{pp} d_{pn} B(c_{nn}, d_{nn})$ for all $c = \bigoplus_{p=1}^{n} c_{pp} \in \mathcal{Z}(\mathcal{G})$;
\item[(vi)] $B(c_{rr}, B(c_{kl}, c_{nn})) = B(B(c_{rr}, c_{kl}), c_{nn})$.
\end{enumerate}

Let $f : \mathcal{G} \times \mathcal{G} \to \mathcal{G}$ be a map satisfying:
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(vii)] $f(\mathcal{G}, 0) = f(0, \mathcal{G}) = 0$;
\item[(viii)] $B(f(x,y), z) = f(B(x,z), B(y,z))$ for all $x,y,z \in \mathcal{G}$;
\item[(ix)] $B(z, f(x,y)) = f(B(z,x), B(z,y))$ for all $x,y,z \in \mathcal{G}$.
\end{enumerate}

What is the value of $f(x,y)$ for all $x,y \in \mathcal{G}$?
